  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Prayer to the Northern Dipper for the Resolution of Calamities and Omens
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Offering

    The sublime Way is soundless, scentless—
    though we cannot fathom its depths,
    yet through clarity and faith we make our offering,
    worthy to present before the altar.
    We bow with sincere hearts,
    pouring our devotion upward to the Lord of Heaven.

    Second Offering

    To seek blessings that do not return—
    would that not be to ask in vain?
    Yet our utmost sincerity never falters;
    we deepen only in reverence and humility.
    Bold in our presumption, we present this prayer,
    pleading to receive the grace of the Great Creator.

    Final Offering

    That disasters and portents are sent as warnings
    stems from the heart of compassion itself.
    Tremblings before the celestial decree,
    we perform these solemn rites with veneration,
    offering our sincerity, though we dare disturb the Most High.
    Though unworthy, bearing this weighty burden of state,
    we confess: governance has strayed from balance,
    disturbing the harmony of yin and yang.

    Thunder rolled repeatedly through the eighth and ninth months,
    defying autumn's proper season;
    heaven's waters fell across a hundred leagues,
    damaging the fields and crops.
    In the night of the己巳 day,
    the moon's path crossed the Azure Dragon's house,
    and strange omens multiplied throughout the days.
    How could we not exhaust ourselves in reform?

    We raise this sacred altar,
    perform these purified rites with reverence.
    May you swiftly grant your blessing and acceptance,
    silently dispelling the transgressions of days past,
    bringing peace and joy to those yet to come.
    May your grace flourish and multiply—
    let the six energies flow through all seasons,
    and preserve the Three Han under heaven's care for ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Han (三韓) refers to the traditional Korean kingdoms of Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla, used here to represent Korea itself.
  - key: ''
    value: The Azure Dragon (蒼龍) represents the eastern celestial quadrant in traditional East Asian cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The six energies (六氣) refer to the six qi or vital forces: wind, cold, heat, dryness, dampness, and fire, which govern the seasons.'
  - key: ''
    value: This is a Daoist ceremonial prayer in the form of a blue note (靑詞), presented in three offerings to petition the celestial powers for relief from calamities.
